{{Orphan|date=September 2014}}

The '''Jaya Chandrika,''' also known as the '''Jayachandrika,'''<ref>J.K Sahu. Historical Value of the Jayachandrika, in Orissa Historical Research Journal,  val. XV, 1964, Nos 3 and 4, p.38</ref> is a [[history|historical]] work composed in 1792<ref>http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/14355/9/09_chapter%204.pdf</ref> by Prahallad Dubey,<ref>http://www.southasiaarchive.com/Content/sarf.120007/202489/009</ref> the [[court poet]] of [[Sarangarh]]. It was written in the [[Lariya language]] for Chauhan, the [[monarch|ruler]] of [[Sambalpur]].<ref>http://kddf.files.wordpress.com/2012/01/method-of-legitimation-of-kingdom-sambalpur.pdf</ref>

==Plot==
Jay Chandirka [[narrator|narrates]] the tale, about the [[Debellatio|defeat]] and death of Prthviraj Chauhan at the hands of the [[Muslim]]s. During this [[armed conflict|conflict]], Chauan's [[Queen consort|queen]] escaped to Patnagarh in West Odisha and was sheltered in the [[house]] of Chakradhara Panigrahi, where she [[childbirth|gave birth]] to Ramai Deva. Deva eventually became the [[founding father|founder]] of Chauhan rule in West Odisha.

The [[narrative|story]] is told with some modifications in the [[Gazetteer]]s, [[travel diary|travel accounts]] and [[indigenous peoples|Indigenous]] records dealing with the Chauhanas of Odisha.

