{{For|the poem by Jean Renart named ''Romans de la Rose'' in the manuscript|Guillaume de Dole}} {{italic title}} [[Image:BodleianDouce364Fol8rRomanRoseMirthGladnessLeadDance.jpg|thumb|275px|Mirth and Gladness lead a Dance in this miniature from a manuscript of the ''Roman de la Rose'' in the [[Bodleian Library]] (MS Douce 364, folio 8r).]] '''''Le Roman de la Rose''''' (English: '''''The Romance of the Rose''''') is a [[Middle Ages|medieval]] [[France|French]] [[Poetry|poem]] styled as an [[allegory|allegorical]] [[dream vision]]. It is a notable instance of [[Courtly love#Literary convention|courtly literature]]. The work's stated purpose is to both entertain and to teach others about the art of [[Romance (love)|romantic love]]. Throughout the poem, ''Rose'' is used both as the name of the titular lady and as a symbol of [[Human female sexuality|female sexuality]]. The other characters' names also function both as regular names and as abstractions illustrating the various factors that are involved in a [[affair|love affair]].
The poem was written in two stages. The first 4,058 lines, written by [[Guillaume de Lorris]] circa 1230, describe the attempts of a [[courtier]] to woo his beloved. This part of the story is set in a walled garden (a ''[[locus amoenus]]''), a traditional [[literary topos]] in [[Epic poetry|epic]] and [[Chivalric romance|chivalric literature]]. Around 1275, [[Jean de Meun]] composed an additional 17,724 lines. In this enormous [[coda (music)|coda]], allegorical personages (Reason, Genius, and so on) hold forth on love.
==Reception== [[Image:Meister des Rosenromans 001.jpg|thumb|left|Genius of love, Meister des Rosenromans, 1420-1430]] ===Early=== The work was both popular and controversial. It was one of the most widely read works in France for three centuries, and it was possibly the most read book in Europe in the 14th and 15th centuries.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Clark|first1=Kenneth|title=Civilisation 03: Romance and Reality|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R8cm8wBKxXs&t=720s|website=YouTube|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref> Its emphasis on sensual language and imagery provoked attacks by [[Jean Gerson]], [[Christine de Pizan]] and many other writers and moralists of the 14th and 15th centuries. Historian [[Johan Huizinga]] writes: "It is astonishing that the Church, which so rigorously repressed the slightest deviations from dogma of a speculative character, suffered the teaching of this [[breviary]] of the aristocracy (for the ''Roman de la Rose'' was nothing else) to be disseminated with impunity."<ref>Huizinga, Johann, ''The Waning of the Middle Ages'' (New York: Anchor Books, 1989) p. 334 {{ISBN|0-385-09288-1}}</ref>
===Modern=== Later reactions suggested that it had a tenuous [[encyclopedic]] quality. The nineteenth-century scholar and writer [[Gaston Paris]] wrote that it was "an encyclopedia in disorder" and British author [[C. S. Lewis]] described it as having an "encyclopedic character".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Doody|first1=Aude|title=Pliny's encyclopedia : the reception of the Natural history|date=2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, UK|isbn=978-0-511-67707-6|page=186}}</ref> One historian wrote that while ''Roman de la Rose'' is obviously not an encyclopedia, "it evokes one, represents one, dreams one, perhaps, with all its aspirations and limitations".{{sfn|Franklin-Brown|2012|p=214}}
==Manuscripts and incunabula== [[File:Roman de la Rose f. 28r (Author at writing desk).jpg|thumb|150px|Author of a 14th-century copy of ''Roman de la Rose'' at his writing desk. [[National Library of Wales|NLW]] MS 5016D]] About 300 manuscripts are extant,<ref>[http://romandelarose.org/#project ''Roman de la Rose'' Digital Library, Project History]</ref> one of the highest figures for a secular work. Many of these are illustrated, most with fewer than ten remaining illustrations, but there are a number with twenty or more illustrations,<ref>[http://romandelarose.org/#select;NUM_ILLUSTRATIONS ''Roman de la Rose'' Digital Library]; not complete</ref> and the exceptional [[Duchy of Burgundy|Burgundian]] [[British Library]] Harley MS 4425 has 92 large and high quality miniatures, despite a date around 1500; the text was copied by hand from a printed edition. These are by the artist known as the [[Master of the Prayer Books of around 1500]], commissioned by Count [[Engelbert II of Nassau]].<ref>[http://www.bl.uk/onlinegallery/onlineex/remarkmanu/roman/ British Library]</ref> The peak period of production was the 14th century, but manuscript versions continued to be produced until the advent of printing, and indeed afterwards – there are at least seven manuscripts dated after 1500.<ref>[http://romandelarose.org/#select;DATE ''Roman de la Rose'' Digital Library]</ref> There are also seven [[incunabula]] printed editions before 1500, the first from [[Geneva]] in about 1481, followed by two from [[Lyon]]s in the 1480s and four from Paris in the 1490s.<ref>[http://istc.bl.uk/search/search.html?operation=search&rsid=1053196&sort=idx-title British Library], [[Incunabula Short Title Catalogue]]</ref> An edition from Lyons in 1503 is illustrated with 140 [[woodcut]]s.<ref>[http://romandelarose.org/#book;Rosen0917 Rosenwald 917], [[Library of Congress]]</ref> Digital images of more than 140 of these manuscripts are available for study in the [[Roman de la Rose Digital Library|''Roman de la Rose'' Digital Library]].
==Translation and influence== Part of the story was translated from its original [[Old French]] into [[Middle English]] as ''[[The Romaunt of the Rose]]'', which had a great influence on English literature. [[Geoffrey Chaucer|Chaucer]] was familiar with the original French text, and a portion of the Middle English translation is thought to be his work. Critics suggest that the character of "La Vieille" acted as source material for Chaucer's Wife of Bath. There were several other early translations into languages including [[Middle Dutch]] (Heinrik van Aken, c. 1280). ''Il Fiore'' is a "reduction" of the poem into 232 Italian [[sonnet]]s by a "ser Durante", sometimes thought to have been [[Dante Alighieri|Dante]], although this is generally thought unlikely. Dante never mentions the ''Roman'', but is often said to have been highly conscious of it in his own work. In 1900, the pre-Raphaelite [[Frederick Startridge Ellis|F. S. Ellis]] translated the whole of the poem into English verse. [[C. S. Lewis]]'s 1936 study ''[[The Allegory of Love]]'' renewed interest in the poem.
