'''Sonata''' was a 3D building design software application developed in the early 1980s and now regarded as the forerunner of today's [[building information modeling|building information modelling]] applications.<ref name=Eastman1>{{cite book|last1=Eastman|first1=Chuck|last2=Tiecholz|first2=Paul|last3=Sacks|first3=Rafael|last4=Liston |first4=Kathleen |title=BIM Handbook: a Guide to Building Information Modeling for owners, managers, designers, engineers, and contractors |date=2008 |publisher= John Wiley |location= Hoboken, New Jersey|isbn=9780470185285|edition=1st|pages=xi-xii}}</ref><ref name=Eastman2>{{cite book|last1= Eastman|first1=Chuck|last2=Tiecholz|first2=Paul|last3=Sacks|first3=Rafael|last4=Liston|first4=Kathleen |year= 2011 |title= BIM Handbook: A Guide to Building Information Modeling for Owners, Managers, Designers, Engineers and Contractors | location = Hoboken, New Jersey|publisher=John Wiley|edition=2nd |pages=36–37}}</ref>
Sonata was commercially released in 1986,<ref name=See>{{cite news|last1=See|first1=Richard|title=Building Information Models and Model Views|url=https://www.wbdg.org/pdfs/jbim_fall07.pdf|accessdate=17 October 2015|work=Journal of Building Information Modelling|issue=Fall|publisher=BuildingSmart Alliance|date=2007}}</ref> having been developed by Jonathan Ingram independently and was sold to T2 Solutions (renamed from [[GMW Architects|GMW Computers]] in 1987<ref name=Port>{{cite book|last1=Port|first1=Stanley|title=The Management of CAD for Construction|date=1989|publisher=Springer|location=New York|isbn=9781468466058}}</ref> - which was eventually bought by Alias|Wavefront),<ref name=Day>{{cite news|last1=Day|first1=Martyn|title=Intelligent Architectural Modeling|url=http://www.caddigest.com/subjects/aec/select/Intelligent_modeling_day.htm|accessdate=15 June 2015|work=AEC Magazine|date=September 2002|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419072947/http://www.caddigest.com/subjects/aec/select/Intelligent_modeling_day.htm|archivedate=19 April 2015|df=}}</ref> and was sold as a successor to GMW's [[RUCAPS]]. It ran on workstation computer hardware (by contrast, other 2D [[Computer-aided design|CAD]] systems could run on personal computers). The system was not expensive, according to Michael Phiri.<ref name=Phiri>{{cite book|last1=Phiri|first1=Michael|title=Information Technology in construction design|date=1999|publisher=Thomas Telford Publishing|location=London|isbn=0 7277 2673 0|page=181}}</ref> Reiach Hall purchased "three Sonata workstations on Silicon Graphics machines, at a total cost of approximately £2000 each" [1990 prices]. Approximately 1000 seats were sold between 1985 and 1992. However, as a BIM application, in addition to geometric modelling, it could model complete buildings, including complex parametrics, costs and staging of the construction process.<ref name=MorganZampi>{{cite book|last1=Morgan|first1=L|last2=Zampi|first2=G|title=Virtual Architecture|date=1999|publisher=Batsford|location=London|page=74|accessdate=17 October 2015}}</ref>
A large number of projects were designed and built using Sonata including [[Peddle Thorp]] Architect's [[Rod Laver Arena]] in 1987, and Gatwick Airport North Terminal Domestic Facility by [[Taylor Woodrow]].<ref name="Fisher et al">{{cite book|last1=Fisher|first1=Norman|last2=Barlow|first2=Richard|title=Project Modelling in Construction: Seeing is believing|date=1997|publisher=Thomas Telford Services Ltd|location=London|page=74|accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref> The US-based architect [[HKS, Inc.|HKS]] used the software in 1992 to design a horse racing facility ([[Lone Star Park]] in [[Grand Prairie]], [[Texas]]) and subsequently purchased the successor product, Reflex.<ref name=McFarlane>{{cite news|last1=McFarlane|first1=Brian|title=How a major design firm adapted to a paradigm shift|url=http://www.healthcaredesignmagazine.com/article/how-major-design-firm-adapted-paradigm-shift|accessdate=17 October 2015|work=Healthcare Design|date=31 March 2008}}</ref>
The Sonata business was founded in 1984 and, by one account it "disappeared in a mysterious, corporate black hole, somewhere in eastern Canada in 1992,"<ref name=Crotty>{{cite book|last1=Crotty|first1=Ray|title=The Impact of Building Information Modelling: Transforming Construction|date=2012|publisher=SPON/Routledge|location=London|isbn=9781136860560|page=71}}</ref> after new owner Alias Research discontinued marketing of the product.<ref>Weisberg, David (2008), ''The Engineering Design Revolution: The People, Companies and Computer Systems That Changed Forever the Practice of Engineering''. Chapter 16. Available [http://cadhistory.net/ online]. Retrieved: 17 October 2015</ref> Ingram then went on to develop [[Reflex (building design software)|Reflex]], bought out by Parametric Technology Corporation ([[PTC (software company)|PTC]]) in 1996.<ref name=Crotty />
As of 2016, Sonata continues to run on an occasional basis at BAM Construct (UK) in [[St Albans]], making it the oldest running BIM system in the world.{{CN|date=July 2016}}
